body:

#### text-block ####
text:

"We can work together to break down rules that stand in the way of building new housing and
that keep families from moving to growing, dynamic cities.” A quote from [SPUR](http://www.spur.org/)? A real estate lobbyist? Your libertarian cousin? Guess again: that was President Barack Obama. 

The White House released a “Housing Development Toolkit” [paper](https://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/whitehouse.gov/files/images/Housing_Development_Toolkit%20f.2.pdf) today urging cities to reduce zoning regulations and increase their housing stock to ease increasing trends of economic segregation.

The diagnosis is stated plainly: “In just the last 10 years, the number of very low-income renters paying more than half their income for rent has increased by almost 2.5 million households, to 7.7 million nationwide, in part because barriers to housing development are limiting housing supply.”

Correlated with a drastic increase in local zoning and permitting regulations in American municipalities, the paper notes a commensurate divergence in home prices and construction costs. While the cost of construction has remained relatively stable in the same time period, home prices skyrocketed. The paper suggests this growing gap is due to “land use restrictions that make developable land much more costly than it is inherently…and unnecessarily slow permitting processes.”
